column2: open-source template for Microsoft® Excel® 2007 and 2010 that makes it easy to explore network graphs.  With NodeXL

column4: click a button and see your graph
column5: all in the familiar environment of the Excel window. column1: 290 "KQur8k" "Nomenklatura" "enriching" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/enriching" "Q123750937" "enriching" "882" "Nomenklatura" "Nomenklatura is a reference data recon server. It is a service that allows users to define and manage manage lists of canonical entities (e.g. person or organization names) and aliases that connect to one of the canonical entities.  This helps to clean up messy data in which a single entity may be referred to by many names.It includes a user interface
column2: an API
column3: and a reconciliation endpoint for OpenRefine for matching data from data sets with the canonical entries. By submitting data to Nomenklatura
column4: users agree to license it under the terms of the Open Database License." NA

350 "QGsf6v" "Omeka.net" "publishing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/publishing" "Q3972943" "publishing" "1447" "Omeka S" "Omeka.net provides a web-publishing platform to curate collections and create exhibitions of digitized content. Omeka.net has grown out of the Omeka project. Omeka.net provides some of the same functionality as Omeka
column2: but does not require the user to provide hosting or to maintain their installation in any way. However
column3: use of Omeka.net limits customization
column4: and hosting more than 500MB of content requires a paid account. Objects in the collection can be cataloged with Dublin core metadata fields and georeferenced for display on a map. Omeka.net includes several plugins
column5: including COinS (which makes objects in Omeka accessible to citations management software
column6: like Zotero)
column7: HTML5 Media (to play audio and video)
column8: and Library of Congress Suggest (which will auto-populate fields with LoC authority and subject headings)." "Q98732070"

column1: 361 "3QBtXR" "OmniPage" "scanning" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/scanning" "Q59155052" "scanning" "1213" "OmniPage" "A software tool capable of performing Optical Character Recognition (OCR) upon a set of images. It was one of the first OCR recognition software to be developed. It was developed in the late 1980s and sold by Caere Corporation. It is currently owned by  Kofax Inc. It achieves the task by analysing pixel sets and in an image and cross-matching them to a dictionary of words. Omnipage automates large sections of the digitisation process enabling physical objects to be scanned
column2: processed using the OCR software and exported to a document file format. Later versions of the software incorporate image enhancement features to improve scan quality (and recognition results) and better support for complex page layouts and forms.Features: Integration with scanning softwareMaintain layout of captured document" "Q3227436"

column1: 370 "eG1HXL" "Onodo" "networkAnalysis" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/networkAnalysis" "Q4417999" "network analysis" "720" "Onodo" "Onodo is a user friendly tool for doing basic visualisation and analysis within a browser making it cross-platform right out of the box. Data can be entered via their intuitive
column2: in-browser node and edge creation tables or imported from a file. As data is added it is instantly previewed and displayed. The visual appearance can be tweaked on the fly and customised in a variety of ways (including applying a unique image or URL to each node). Once created
column3: visualisations can be embedded and shared outside of the Onodo browser environment. Moreover
column4: with a click of a button
column5: Onodo calculates standard network parameters such as betweenness
column6: closeness and displays these values within the table. It calculates and demonstrates basic network parameters and measures quickly and allows for the creation of chapters that cement using the visualisation as a data-driven narrative device." NA

387 "MHE8cr" "Open Conference Systems" "publishing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/publishing" "Q3972943" "publishing" "1420" "Open Conference Systems" "Open Conference Systems (OCS) is a free Web publishing tool that can create a complete Web presence for scholarly conferences. It is a highly flexible management and publishing system that can be downloaded for free and installed on a local Web server. It has been designed to reduce the time and energy devoted to the clerical and managerial tasks associated with managing a conference
column2: while improving the record-keeping and efficiency of editorial processes. It seeks to improve the scholarly and public quality of conference publishing through a number of innovation
column3: from making policies more transparent to improving indexing. Features:- create a conference Web site- Manage conferences that occur more than once (e.g.
column4: yearly)- compose and send a call for papers- electronically accept paper and abstract submissions- allow paper submitters to edit their work- Conduct peer reviews- post conference proceedings and papers in a searchable format- Schedule a Conference- post the original data sets- register participants
column5: including accepting payments- integrate post-conference online discussions- utilize an e-mail template system- support multiple languages with localization files- Take advantage of more customizable
column6: scalable and secure codeSystem Requirements:A server environment meeting the following requirements is recommended:- PHP >= 4.2.x (including PHP 5.x); Microsoft IIS requires PHP 5.x- MySQL >= 3.23.23 (including MySQL 4.x) or PostgreSQL >= 7.1 (including- PostgreSQL 8.x)- Apache >= 1.3.2x or >= 2.0.4x or Microsoft IIS 6Operating system: Any OS that supports the above software
column8: BSD

column1: 449 "Q8EqLI" "OrlandoVision (OVis)" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "5" "OrlandoVision (OVis)" "An application for visualizing a specific collection of authors
column2: and the links or associations between them.  Links are determined by co-occurrence in the Orlando dataset.  The current dataset consists of authors
column3: other people associated with them
column4: and the text entries upon which these associations are based.  The application is designed in such a way that it could be extended to use other datasets as well.The display can be customized in the several ways.  Node colours
column5: shapes and sizes can be altered.  More significantly
column6: the layout of the graph can be chosen from amongst several different algorithms.As the collection is quite large
column7: there are many filtering options available.  In terms of author
column8: the following categories can be specified: gender
column10: and author nationality.  The user can create complex search queries of the authors and the text
column11: and specify a date restriction for the authors' life span.Each association in the text has been tagged with one or more semantic attributes
column12: i.e. the type or meaning of the relation between the people.  These tags have been organized into a tree
column13: moving from general to more specific relations.  Each tag in the tree can be checked/unchecked
column15: a data set and customizations can be saved as a session which can then be loaded at a later time.  In addition
column16: screenshots of the current layout can be saved to an image file." NA

column1: 454 "qmz8q2" "OSoMe" "modeling" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/modeling" "Q1116876" "scientific modeling" "1551" "OSoMe" "OSoMe (awe•some) is a joint project of the Indiana University Network Science Institute (IUNI) and the Center for Complex Networks and Systems Research (CNetS)
column2: aimed to study information diffusion in social media. Here we highlight findings
column3: publications
column4: and resources. Use our tools to explore how ideas spread through online social networks.

column1: Hoaxy: Visualize the spread of claims and fact checking.
Botometer: Check how bot-like a Twitter user behaves.
Fakey: PLay this game to learn to recognize fake news on your social feed.
Trends: Compare when memes gain and lose popularity.
Networks: Explore who is discussing a meme and what memes are related.
Maps: Examine where people are talking about a meme over time.
Movies: Generate movies of how conversations about a meme evolve over time.
EchoDemo: Simulation demonstrating how two basic mechanisms of social media can lead to polarized social networks.
Bot Electioneering Volume: Visualizing the activity of likely bots on Twitter around the 2018 US midterm elections.
As well as API and Enhanced Data available." NA

539 "6wZpca" "Participad" "collaborating" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/collaborating" "Q1145523" "collaborating" "922" "Participad" "Participad is a WordPress plugin that allows multiple people to edit the same WP content at the same time. Powered by Etherpad Lite
column2: Participad gives you: notepads for collaborative notetaking; synchronous authoring of any content in the WordPress Dashboard; front-end editing. You can download it from the WordPress plugin repository. Participad has three modules: Dashboard – The Dashboard module puts Etherpad editors into the WordPress Dashboard. Participad removes the “Visual” and “HTML” tabs from the standard WP editor
column3: and replaces them with a “Participad” tab.Frontend – The Frontend module allows users to edit WordPress content from the front end of your website – no Dashboard required. Participad modifies the Edit links on your posts and pages so that
column4: instead of leading to the Dashboard
column5: the static content of your post is swapped with an editable Etherpad window.Notepad – The Notepad module enables a new WordPress Post Type called Notepads. Notepads are collaborative note-taking documents
column6: which can optionally be linked to existing static posts or pages. Participad provides several shortcodes and widgets that make it easy to create new Notepads from the front end of your website. N.B. Participad requires a separate Etherpad Lite Installation." NA

column1: 722 "Q3anVk" "Prismatic" "discovering" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/discovering" "Q12772819" "discovering" "797" "Prismatic" "Content curation and topic discovery website based primarily on publishers the user follows through social media.Upon signing up
column2: users are asked to select a number of topics that fall within their fields of interest. Relevant content is shown in a vertical feed. Users have the option to recommend
column3: comment
column4: share
column5: remove the content from their feed
column6: or save it. Prismatic \"learns\" from your behaviour which topics and publishers are of most interest to you. They say the more people who use it the better it gets
column7: as recommendations figure greatly into popularity rankings. There are no human editors
column8: just algorithms.Promoted features include connecting with communities who share your interests
column9: learning from users who work in your field
column10: the ability to share your discoveries with friends
column11: and taking a \"deep dive on any topic.\"According to Aria Haghighi
column12: one of the founders \"...we have an architecture similar to a search engine: polling and crawling the open web and activity on social networks.\" A 2013 article on Slate.com refers to Prismatic as \"the world's smartest news reader\". It's a good addition to other search and curation tools such as Google Alerts and saved Twitter hashtag searches. It aims to be better than the rest through use of parameters that are not static; it adjusts to your preferences as well as trending content on other social media sites." "Q7245690"

column1: 767 "JuW2vQ" "Protégé" "identifying" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/identifying" "Q3265221" "identification" "933" "Protégé" "The Protege Project offers WebProtege and Protege Desktop
column2: which are free and open source ontology editing applications.WebProtégé is an ontology development environment for the Web that makes it easy to create
column3: upload
column4: modify
column5: and share ontologies for collaborative viewing and editing. WebProtégé fully supports the latest OWL 2 Web Ontology Language. The highly configurable user interface creates the perfect environment for beginners and experts alike. Collaboration features abound
column6: including sharing and permissions
column8: watches and email notifications. RDF/XML
column12: and other formats available for ontology upload and download.Protégé Desktop is a feature rich ontology editing environment with full support for the OWL 2 Web Ontology Language
column13: and direct in-memory connections to description logic reasoners like HermiT and Pellet. Protégé Desktop supports creation and editing of one or more ontologies in a single workspace via a completely customizable user interface. Visualization tools allow for interactive navigation of ontology relationships. Advanced explanation support aids in tracking down inconsistencies. Refactor operations available including ontology merging

column1: 774 "sSy5hU" "Ptolemaic" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "877" "Ptolemaic" "Ptolemaic is a computer application for music visualization and analysis written in the Java programming language. The software is designed to aid in the analysis of all types of Western music using established analytical techniques
column2: including tonal functional analysis (Harrison 1994)
column3: pitch-class set analysis (Forte 1973)
column4: hierarchical linear analysis (Schenker 1935
column5: Jones 2002)
column6: tonal pitch-space analysis on the Tonnetz (Riemann 1915)
column8: and transformation analysis (Lewin 1987). Musical works and excerpts may be opened and saved using the de-facto standard music notation interchange format
column10: Ptolemaic can display the music on a pitch/time graph
column12: on a step-class/time graph (also called a diatonic lattice) (Jones 2002)
column14: or using filtered point-symmetry (Douthett 2008). Pitch classes and chords are color coded so that the user can easily correlate them across each graph. The benefit of having a software tool to visualize and perform certain analysis tasks is in automating processes that are normally time-consuming for the musician
column15: thus allowing the music scholar to focus on the musical issues
column16: rather than the technical issues of graphing
column17: and calculating chord classes. Ptolemaic provides useful ways of visualizing a piece of music and tools for gaining more information about that music
column18: so that the user can efficiently make informed musical decisions about the music and preserve that analysis for future study." NA

column1: 902 "QsW4z8" "RefWorks" "organizing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/organizing" "Q36993249" "organizing" "1180" "RefWorks" "RefWorks allows users to create personal databases and use them for a variety of research activities. References are quickly and easily imported from text files or online databases. The databases can then be used to manage
column2: store
column3: and share the information. Users can automatically insert references from their database into their papers and generate formatted bibliographies and manuscripts in seconds.RefWorks allows you to…Organize and create a personal database online – no more index cards to write out and organize. Everything is done automatically as you import the reference into RefWorks.Format bibliographies and manuscripts in seconds – this saves hours of typing time and decreases the number of errors in creating tedious bibliographies. Easily make changes to your paper and reformat in seconds.Import references from a variety of databases using the already created Import Filters.Manage Alerts – RefWorks has incorporated a RSS feed reader to allow you to establish links to your favorite RSS feeds and import data from those feeds directly into RefWorks.Searching your RefWorks database is fast and easy – RefWorks automatically creates author
column4: descriptor and periodical indexes when importing so you just click on the word to perform the retrieval. Use Quick Search to search all fields for the most comprehensive results or Advanced Search to narrow your search to specific terms and fields." "Q7307076"

column4: RSiena is optimized for social network data
column5: but is also applicable to other forms of network data

1086 "CiFvAR" "Siena (Simulation Investigation for Empirical Network Analysis)" "analyzing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/analyzing" "Q217602" "analyzing" "522" "Siena (Simulation Investigation for Empirical Network Analysis)" "Siena (Simulation Investigation for Empirical Network Analysis) is a free program for statistical analysis developed particularly to work with social network data
column2: but also applicable to other forms of network data. It models network dynamics via Markov chain models; this approach is best applied to data where relations between actors and their behaviour can be treated as a state rather than as an event. Siena's statistical analysis processes can be time-consuming
column3: as the system works via computer simulation of the network. It was in continuous development from 2001 through 2010
column4: releasing versions up to 3.2. Development on Siena as a stand-alone program has concuded
column5: and the project has shifted focus to RSiena
column6: a version of Siena deployed in R." NA

1442 "DToKG9" "TerraME" "programming" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/programming" "Q80006" "computer programming" "1542" "TerraME" "TerraME is a programming environment for spatial dynamical modelling. It supports cellular automata
column2: agent-based models
column3: and network models running in 2D cell spaces. TerraME provides an interface to TerraLib geographical database
column4: allowing models direct access to geospatial data. Its modelling language has in-built functions that makes it easier to develop multi-scale and multi-paradigm models for environmental applications.

column1: Two important innovations in TerraME are its use of anisotropic spaces and of hybrid automata models. Anisotropic spaces arise when modeling natural and human-related phenomena. For example
column2: land settlers in a new area do not occupy all places at the same time. They follow roads and rivers
column3: leading to an anisotropic pattern. Anisotropic spaces are implemented in TerraME using Generalized Proximity Matrices (GPM). The GPM is an extension of the usual definition of the spatial relations and include a combination of neighborhood measures in the absolute space and in the relative space.

column1: A hybrid automaton is an abstract model for a system whose behavior has discrete and continuous parts. It extends the idea of finite automata to allow continuous change to take place between transitions. Adopting hybrid automata in spatial dynamical models allows complex models which include critical transitions." NA

With the large number of documents stored on your computer and online links that you might use
column2: this is a helpful application that allows you to navigate the environment more easily. Although the feature set is now well developed
column3: an inexperienced user should still be able to use it relatively easily. It is not intended only for the expert managers.The key features of the application are therefore as follows:1. The ability to read text
column4: XML
column5: or parse the contents of PDF or online content (HTML). Binary (Microsoft Office) files are included in the professional version.2. A set of filter operations that can be applied in sequences
column6: saved and retrieved.3. A set of folders can be used as default locations for all of your related data. The application runs locally only
column7: there is no requirement for a remote server.4. A grid or tabular format allows you to view database queries
column8: or for operations over specific columns or cells. A log file might have a standard format that can be queried
column9: or conversion to CSV might be required
column10: for example.5. An analysis panel allows you to select single or groups of files and compare the content based on known clustering algorithms. Also some basic statistical counts.6. Basic search from a toolbar
column11: or more complex search operations from a Query form. The search facilities allow you to find information from different views and query types.7. A separate Organiser application allows you to store your online links or local files
column12: into ordered books and categories that can also be searched over. This allows for querying most of the available information

column16: for any type of file. You can open one of your commonly viewed files or links through a single click." NA

The aim is to facilitate ordinary users to formulate semantically unambiguous queries so as to support the fast and precise access to information. column2: it contains all the texts of these poems in the original Greek. In addition
column3: the Chicago Homer includes English and German translations

column7: and the German translations of the Iliad and Odyssey by Johan Heinrich Voss. Through the associated web site Eumaios users of the Chicago Homer can also from each line of the poem access pertinent Iliad Scholia and papyrus readings.  " NA

column1: 1583 "6TkOVr" "The Field Linguist’s Toolbox" "creating" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/creating" "Q123819227" "creating" "1289" "The Field Linguist’s Toolbox" "Toolbox is a data management and analysis tool for field linguists. It is especially useful for maintaining lexical data
column2: and for parsing and interlinearizing text
column3: but it can be used to manage virtually any kind of data. Toolbox is free to download and use.

column1: Toolbox is especially powerful for handling large corpora and dictionaries. It can handle a corpus of over a million words
column2: and a dictionary of hundreds of thousands of words

column1: At heart
column2: Toolbox is a text-oriented database management system (DBMS) with added functionality designed to meet the needs of a field linguist. The underlying DBMS offers full user flexibility in the design of any type of database. But for ease of use
column3: the Toolbox package includes prepared database definitions for a typical dictionary and text corpus. Toolbox also has powerful linguistic functionality. It includes a morphological parser that can handle almost all types of morphophonemic processes. It has a word formula component that allows the linguist to describe all the possible affix patterns that occur in words. It has a user-definable interlinear text generation system which uses the morphological parser and lexicon to generate annotated text" NA

column1: 1590 "jpne6X" "The Macro-Etymological Analyzer" "contentAnalysis" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/contentAnalysis" "Q653137" "content analysis" "805" "The Macro-Etymological Analyzer" "Formerly a web based app
column2: the Macro-Etymological Analyzer is  now available as a Command-line app. It is used for text analysis. It will look up every word of your text in the Etymological Wordnet
column3: and generate statistics about the macro-etymology of your text
column4: organized by language family. For instance
column5: it can analyze a novel and tell you the proportions of words of Anglo-Saxon origin
column6: or of Afroasiatic origin. First-generation and second-generation language ancestor data is included
column7: and the output is highly granular
column8: allowing the scholar to see the origins of individual words
column9: and statistics about each ancestor language. This data can be useful as a particular type of topic modeling
column10: since some macro-etymological data have have been correlated with particular genres
column11: as well as the ages and sexes of their authors and/or speaking characters. For more details
column12: read the introductory blog post and see these example experiments." NA

column2: T-PEN developed a model for enabling users working on transcription projects in T-PEN to export their work to a larger
column3: external project. In this instance
column4: the CCL prepared for T-PEN an XML-markup template (XML button set) that may be used for all transcriptions destined for the CCL database. Users identify their T-PEN projects as destined for the CCL
column5: and when the transcription is complete
column6: they can submit it from T-PEN to the CCL project. The CCL receives notification of the stable URL in T-PEN that the CCL can (either manually or by automation) use to extract the designated transcription from T-PEN’s data store. column8: a dictionary for Middle English and the Dictionary of Old English (subscription required). User can select which tools will be available in the Transcription UI’s i-frame. All tools can also be renamed by the user on the project management page.Exporting Transcriptions: When exporting xml
column9: users can select or deselect all the tags for inclusion at once.Line History (Versioning): T-PEN distinguishes between all versions of any transcription line. column1: 1722 "phjX9e" "Transformer: a Unicode Transform/Replace Tool" "converting" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/converting" "Q1783551" "data conversion" "1269" "Transformer: a Unicode Transform/Replace Tool" "Transformer loads Unicode text files and performs sequences of transformation operations on them — search-and-replace
column2: or JavaScript operations. It provides you with an interface to create and test these sequences of transformations before running them in batch mode on a set of files.

column1: Transformer was created to assist in the rescue of textual data from obsolete file formats such as DOS word-processor files. Sometimes
column2: it proves impossible to rescue old data through normal means such as running the original application and exporting to a format which can be imported by a more modern program. Perhaps the program which created the data no longer exists or cannot be run on available hardware
column3: or perhaps it cannot save to any format but its own. In these circumstances
column4: it is often necessary to rescue the data by a process of manual conversion
column5: identifying blocks of text or other data in the original file which can be replaced with Unicode characters
column6: and building sequences of replacement operations which gradually convert the data. This often requires an exhaustive trial-and-error approach in which transformation operations are added incrementally and tested in various sequences before a reliable sequence is developed; then the sequence can be run on a group of files. Transformer should provide as efficient a working environment as possible
column7: so that the user can focus on the task itself rather than the machinery." NA

column2: which is the cautious comparison of various editions of one and the same text. The traditional approach of a humanities scholar is to put the texts of several editions next to each other and mark the differences among the textual entities (e.g.
column3: sentences
column4: sections
column5: chapters). Since this is an extremely laborious approach many Digital Humanities projects investigate tools that support the humanities scholars with computational methods.TRAViz is a JavaScript library that was developed within the Digital Humanities project eTRACES. It generates visualizations for Text Variant Graphs that show the variations between different editions of texts. TRAViz supports the collation task by providing methods to:- align various editions of a text- visualize the alignment- improve the readability for Text Variant Graphs compared to other approaches- interact with the graph to discover how individual editions disseminate" NA

column6: or temporal indicators based on tense. The developer of this application can be reached on Twitter.

2200 "n4Dv8y" "WordStat - Content Analysis & Text Mining Software" "contentAnalysis" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/contentAnalysis" "Q653137" "content analysis" "935" "WordStat - Content Analysis & Text Mining Software" "WordStat is a text analysis module for QDA Miner or SimStat. WordStat combines content analysis method by using dictionary approach and many algorithms exploration or various text mining methods. WordStat can apply existing categorization dictionaries to a new text corpus. It also may be used in the development and validation of new categorization dictionaries. When used in conjunction with manual coding
column2: this module can provide assistance for a more systematic application of coding rules
column3: help uncover differences in word usage between subgroups of individuals and assist in the revision of existing coding using KWIC (Keyword In Context) tables. WordStat is specifically designed to study textual information such as responses to open-ended questions
column4: interviews
column5: titles
column6: journal articles
column8: electronic communications

column1: 2213 "2qgaRK" "Writefull" "writing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/writing" "Q110484020" "writing" "858" "writefull" "Writefull is a light-weight app that uses data from Google Books (5+ million books) and the Web to improve your writing
column2: It compares small sections of your text to a large data set of writing found online and in Google Books. All you need to do is select a chunk of your text in your browser or text editing software
column3: activate the Writefull popover
column4: and choose one of its five options: 1) check the number of results (how often the chunk appears in Google Books or the Web); 2) compare the number of results (if your selected chunk appears more or less frequently than suggestions from online);3) see examples in context (display several examples of how your selected chunk is used in different texts); 4) find words in context (see which words are used most often in your context
column5: which you specify in your text by a star. For example
column6: 'research should * this issue' will give you a list with 'research should address this issue'
column8: 'research should examine this issue'
column9: etc.); 5) find synonyms in context (see which synonyms of a word are used most often in your context
column10: with you specifying the word you want synonyms for by two stars. For example: 'a *difficult* situation' will suggest 'an awkward situation'
column13: etc). The app works with a small popover which mean you can activate it from whatever writing tool you're using. No need to change windows - no interruption of your workflow. N.B. Writefull 2.0 will be launching soon and will eliminate the need to purchase queries in the Web version. The $5 membership fee still applies." "Q59771338"

2224 "MNn3xQ" "xMod" "creating" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/creating" "Q123819227" "creating" "1381" "xMod" "xMod is a desktop application which can transform a repository of XML into a completely finished website.
The entire process can be setup and run to produce a basic website assuming some prerequisites:
- a set of valid XML files. These would normally comply with a TEI DTD.
- a configuration script that indicates the relationship between files
- a  'personality pack' (CSS and image files) that determine its visual appearance.
However if they are not present
column2: the completed website falls back on a default look and feel.

column1: Some features include:
- Batch file processing
- Modular XSLT structure
column2: with special libraries for different transformation scenarios

column1: - Ability to group files for generation of indices at document and intra-document level" NA

column1: 2406 "Kfm9H2" "BookLamp" "discovering" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/discovering" "Q12772819" "discovering" "349" "BookLamp" "BookLamp
column2: part of the Book Genome Project
column3: is a tool and a resource for finding books. It offers an alternative to social recommendation engines reliant on author popularity by treating its books as equal regardless of number of copies sold. BookLamp's goal is to match users to the books relevant to their interests as accurately as possible. Rather than genres
column4: it uses 'StoryDNA'
column5: which identifies the thematic ingredients important to a book's narrative
column6: in addition to how prominent that ingredient is within the text. BookLamp has been retired as of April 2014 and the website is no longer available. The site has been captured by the Internet Archive
column7: and may still be viewed there via the Wayback Machine." NA

column1: 2483 "B51xcr" "Casual" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "526" "Casual" "Casual is a free
column2: open source tool for generating a visualization of concepts from a key word search. It uses Wikipedia for conceptual information
column3: and can also include Google Image search results where applicable. Users can click on a term to generate a new search from that term
column4: while image results can be rearranged by clicking and dragging them to the desired location. Casual can produce visualizations ranging from 10 to 400 concepts in size
column5: and can retrieve information for queries in a wide variety of languages. This tool is no longer supported; development appears to have ceased in 2009." NA

column1: 2487 "QhIUpI" "CasualConc" "analyzing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/analyzing" "Q217602" "analyzing" "1570" "CasualConc" "CasualConc is a concordance program that runs natively on macOS 10.11 or later. The current version (2.0 or later) can generate Key Word in Context concordance lines
column2: word clusters
column3: collocation analysis
column4: and word count. This program is only tested with English text just because that is the only language but technically
column5: it should be able to handle any language macOS can. This new version (2.0) has visualization functions using the statistical environment R (needs to be installed separately). It works best with plain text files (.txt) encoded in ASCII or UTF-8
column6: but can handle other file types and other encodings.  Reading non-plain text files will take more time to process.  PDF files should be text-embedded." NA

column1: 2519 "HdX4Co" "CHET-C" "converting" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/converting" "Q1783551" "data conversion" "1230" "CHET-C" "CHET-C
column2: or Chapel Hill Electronic Text-Converter
column3: is a browser based software tool designed to convert digital texts that employ standard epigraphic conventions such as the Leiden sigla into EpiDoc-compliant XML files. The tool can be accessed online at http://www.stoa.org/projects/epidoc/stable/chetc-js/chetc.html. Fragments of epigraphic text using standard sigla (eg Leiden convention markup) are pasted into the tool and Epidoc compliant XML is generated.Prior versions exist (MSAccess + VBA and Java
column4: both now deprecated) for use by those without stabel web access or who wish to customise the underlying regular expressions to process non standard sigla" NA

column1: 2525 "Gt1wsh" "Chronos Timeline" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "1536" "Chronos Timeline" "HyperStudio’s Chronos Timeline is designed specifically for needs in the humanities and social sciences to represent time-based data. Chronos allows scholars and students to dynamically present historical data in a flexible online environment. Switching easily between vertical and horizontal orientations
column2: researchers can quickly scan large number of events
column3: highlight and filter events based on subject matter or tags
column4: and recontextualize historical data. The Chronos Timeline is one component in HyperStudio’s emerging Repertoire platform and can easily be integrated with other tools such as faceted browsers
column5: maps
column6: and visualization modules.

column1: Built in JavaScript on top of an extendable object-oriented architecture
column2: Chronos is a flexible jQuery plug-in using the powerful jQuery library. Chronos is notable for its dynamic scaling
column3: which allows the user to drill down into time periods to explore and compare events. Chronos connects flexibly to data sources via the JSON open standard
column4: and will support XML data structures in a future version. Repertoire Chronos Timeline is currently in beta stage and will be released as free software under the GNU General Public License." NA

column1: 2528 "fhIJVa" "Cinco" "programming" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/programming" "Q80006" "computer programming" "1545" "Cinco" "The “CINCO SCCE Meta Tooling Framework” is a generator-driven development environment for domain-specific graphical modeling tools. It is based on the Eclipse Modeling Framework and Graphiti Graphical Tooling Infrastructrure
column2: but aims to hide much of their complexity and intricate APIs.

column1: A graphical modeling tool developed with CINCO is completely generated from an intuitive higher-level abstract specification language. Semantics-inducing parts of the tool that are difficult to define in an abstract declarative way (such as model interpreters
column2: transformations
column3: or code generators) are written in Java against a simple model-based API. CINCO handles the inclusion of the right buttons in the GUI that trigger those actions.

column1: Furthermore
column2: CINCO supports the integration of the Java Application Building Center (jABC) into the development process
column3: so that even people with little or no programming experience can express model behavior in a process-oriented fashion." NA

column2: organise and share the scholarly papers you are reading. When you see a paper on the web that interests you
column3: you can click one button and have it added to your personal library. CiteULike automatically extracts the citation details
column4: so there's no need to type them in yourself. It all works from within your web browser so you can access it from any computer with an Internet connection. CiteULike supports annotation and rating of items
column5: and upload of attachments (e.g. PDF file). (Attachments are only accessible privately by individual users). Bibliographic entries can be imported singly or in batches using BibTex or RIS formats." "Q1093324"

2743 "b5vyBf" "Crossfilter" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "1524" "Crossfilter" "Fast Multidimensional Filtering for Coordinated Views
Crossfilter is a JavaScript library for exploring large multivariate datasets in the browser. Crossfilter supports extremely fast (<30ms) interaction with coordinated views
column2: even with datasets containing a million or more records; we built it to power analytics for Square Register
column3: allowing merchants to slice and dice their payment history fluidly.

column1: Since most interactions only involve a single dimension
column2: and then only small adjustments are made to the filter values
column3: incremental filtering and reducing is significantly faster than starting from scratch. Crossfilter uses sorted indexes (and a few bit-twiddling hacks) to make this possible
column4: dramatically increasing the perfor­mance of live histograms and top-K lists." NA

column1: 2847 "7JufQv" "Datawrapper" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "1509" "wrapper" "Datawrapper is a tool built to make it easy for journalists and other content-creators to create simple charts and maps for web articles. To make a chart
column2: you paste in your numbers and choose a chart type. We make sure that the chart you’ll embed in your article at the end is beautiful
column3: responsive and interactive.

column1: Our charts feel at home on the web. They’re interactive
column2: responsive and embeddable in your website.

column1: No code or design skills required.
The way from data to a beautiful chart is shorter than you think.
1. Copy & Paste your data:
Simply copy your data from Excel or Google Sheets. You can also upload CSV files or link to an URL for live-updating charts.
2. Visualize:
Choose from many chart and map types with one click. Customize and annotate your chart to make it more effective.
3. Publish your chart:
Copy the ready-to-use embed code into your CMS or website
column2: or export the chart as an image or PDF to print it." "Q2594395"

2916 "NkwyDW" "digilib" "collaborating" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/collaborating" "Q1145523" "collaborating" "1205" "digilib" "Digilib is a web based client/server technology for images. The image content is processed on-the-fly by a Java Servlet on the server side so that only the visible portion of the image is sent to the web browser on the client side. It supports a wide range of image formats and viewing options on the server side while only requiring an internet browser with javascript and a low bandwidth internet connection on the client side. digilib enables very detailed work on an image as required by scientists with elaborate zoom features like an option to show images on the screen in their original size. digilib facilitates cooperation of scientists over the internet and novel uses of source material by image annotations and stable references that can be embedded in URLs. digilib is used in the ALCATRAZ framework of image
column2: text and annotation tools and many other projects." NA

column1: 2955 "V6aWAu" "Discursis" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "507" "Discursis" "Discursis is a tool for analyzing text-based natural language with a focus on sequential analysis. It is particularly desgined to work with texts that have an internal temporal structure
column2: such as a transcribed conversation. For each text
column3: it generates a statistics-based internal language model and applies tagging to each temporal unit detected. The model and tagging are then used as the basis for an interactive visualization which permits examination at a various levels of granularity
column4: ranging from a whole-text to a unit-by-unit level; it can also show topic usage patterns within the text. Users must purchase a license; both student and academic trial licenses are available." NA

2966 "2YMYaD" "DocuBurst" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "123" "DocuBurst" "DocuBurst is a free web-based visualization tool for exploring the contents of a text.  Visitors can upload their own text or view those provided by others. DocuBurst presents an interactive chart called a ‘radial sunburst’ diagram which organizes the nouns extracted from the user-supplied text based on their meaning
column2: and colours them based on frequency
column3: revealing common themes in the text.  The visualization also shows the proper nouns (e.g. character names) in a linked word cloud. The visualization may be zoomed
column4: filtered
column5: or refocused to target types of words of interest (e.g. “animal” words or “feeling” words).  The visualization also provides a comparison tool to contrast word use across two documents.  DocuBurst views can be bookmarked
column6: annotated
column8: and embedded in your own website." NA

column1: 2969 "2YMYaD" "DocuBurst" "contentAnalysis" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/contentAnalysis" "Q653137" "content analysis" "123" "DocuBurst" "DocuBurst is a free web-based visualization tool for exploring the contents of a text.  Visitors can upload their own text or view those provided by others. DocuBurst presents an interactive chart called a ‘radial sunburst’ diagram which organizes the nouns extracted from the user-supplied text based on their meaning
column2: and colours them based on frequency
column3: revealing common themes in the text.  The visualization also shows the proper nouns (e.g. character names) in a linked word cloud. The visualization may be zoomed
column4: filtered
column5: or refocused to target types of words of interest (e.g. “animal” words or “feeling” words).  The visualization also provides a comparison tool to contrast word use across two documents.  DocuBurst views can be bookmarked
column6: annotated
column8: and embedded in your own website." NA

column1: 3071 "FHO9mF" "Eris Solver - Free Crowdsolver for Complex Problems" "collaborating" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/collaborating" "Q1145523" "collaborating" "746" "Eris Solver - Free Crowdsolver for Complex Problems" "Eris Solver is a free crowd-solver for complex problems. It implements an innovative way to solve complex problems by adapting brainstorming technique to a Problem Tree Analysis and by channelling Collective Intelligence. When simple problem may require a unique solution to be solved
column2: Complex problems behave differently and multiple solutions are sometimes necessary to solve them. On the contrary to simple problem that may not need further deepening
column3: a complex problem may be broken up in multiple small ones that help us understand the big picture. Every branch of the issue tree represent a different aspect of the problem

3176 "mdEbYT" "FigShare" "capturing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/capturing" "Q123819225" "capturing" "1045" "Figshare" "Figshare is a repository where users can make all of their research outputs available in a citable
column2: shareable and discoverable manner.  All file formats can be published
column3: including videos and datasets that are often demoted to the supplemental materials section in current publishing models. Users of the site maintain full control over the management of their research whilst benefiting from global access
column4: version control and secure backups in the cloud. By opening up the peer review process
column5: researchers can easily publish null results
column6: avoiding the file drawer effect and helping to make scientific research more efficient. Figshare uses creative commons licensing to allow frictionless sharing of research data whilst allowing users to maintain their ownership." "Q17013516"

3289 "ewuTgR" "FromThePage" "capturing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/capturing" "Q123819225" "capturing" "168" "FromThePage" "FromThePage is a free software for manuscript transcription
column2: allowing volunteers to transcribe document pages online. Transcriptions can then be marked up and annotated in a wiki-like enviroment
column3: with the resultant text displayed on the public web. It includes a discussion environment
column4: enabling collaboration on particularly difficult pages. FromThePage is currently in beta
column5: permitting up to 100 pages per project
column6: and is in the process of developing a paid version for larger projects requiring more server space
column7: with price determined primarily by server and maintenance costs. Privacy features are also under development
column8: and further features forthcoming based on feedback from users." NA

column1: 3374 "nNlpSz" "Gerbil" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "841" "Gerbil" "Gerbil is a generic framework for visualization and analysis of multispectral and hyperspectral data that strives to both bring new innovations in analysis capabilities and be of use in a wide range of hyperspectral data applications. In a nutshell
column2: Gerbil lets you…explore a multispectral or hyperspectral image before processing it
column3: apply common computer vision algorithms adapted to hyperspectral data
column4: cluster and label image pixels for your application scenario
column5: assess your own algorithms via high-dimensional data visualization
column6: use an intuitive interface for teaching multispectral imaging and reflectance analysis.One example application for Gerbil is finding hidden information in multispectral scans of old manuscripts or art pieces." NA

column1: 3415 "l9Acyy" "Google Charts" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "368" "Google Charts" "Google Charts (formerly the Google Visualization API) is a web-based interface for interactive data visualization via HTML5 and SVG. It includes a number of preset chart types ranging from line charts to word trees and all are customizable. A separate selection of user community contributed chart types is also available. Within a chart
column2: the API identifies events that users can trigger with presets ranging from simple clicks to Javascript methods

column1: 3522 "bNHxQC" "Hermetic Word Frequency Counter" "analyzing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/analyzing" "Q217602" "analyzing" "749" "Hermetic Word Frequency Counter" "This software scans a Word DOCX file or a text file (including HTML and XML files) with text encoded via ANSI or UTF-8 and counts the frequencies of different words. column2: so the program can be told to allow or disallow words with numerals
column3: hyphens
column4: apostrophes
column5: underscores or colons
column6: to ignore words which are short or which occur infrequently
column7: to treat upper/lower case as significant or not
column8: and to ignore words (e.g.
column10: a.k.a. stop words) contained in a specified file.  This software may be used with text in most European languages.  The language of the text is detected automatically and (if supported) the corresponding stop words file is optionally loaded.  Results can be exported to Excel for further processing.  There is also an Advanced Version with greater functionality." NA

column1: 3523 "BNkp4o" "Hermetic Word Frequency Counter Advanced Version" "analyzing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/analyzing" "Q217602" "analyzing" "748" "Hermetic Word Frequency Counter Advanced Version" "This software scans one or many Word DOCX

The words/phrases which are found can be displayed alphabetically or by frequency.  The program can be told to allow or disallow words with numerals
column3: hyphens

column10: and supports the use of regular expressions for specifying words/phrases to count." NA

column1: 3524 "xQMWDs" "Heurist" "creating" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/creating" "Q123819227" "creating" "766" "Heurist Data Manager / Visualiser / Publisher" "HEURIST  (http://HeuristNetwork.org) is an extremely flexible
column2: end-user oriented
column3: web-based data management system designed specifically for Humanities data. Developed since 2005
column4: it has been in active use across many projects since 2009. It is available both as a free web service for researchers (hosted at the University of Sydney Data Centre) or for installation on a physical or virtual server (Open Source on gitHub). Researchers can design
column5: create
column6: manage
column8: visualise and publish their own richly-structured database(s) through a simple web interface
column9: without the need for programmer(s). Quite complex databases can be built in a few hours by borrowing structures and vocabularies published by other users. Databases can be designed and built incrementally
column10: as existing data are not affected by changes in structure. Databases created by Heurist are stored in MySQL with a repeatable structure facilitating sustainability and independent access by other software. Advanced features include record linking
column20: XSLT transforms. The team provides initial email and skype assistance for project setup at no cost
column21: and special customisations at modest cost.Heurist is applicable in many domains including History
column26: Media Studies etc. It handles everything from text
column28: through networks of rich relationships and offset annotations
column31: spatial data and dating (including non-western systems and dating uncertainty).Sophisticated searches (including faceted and rule-based) can be saved
column32: organised and rendered as layered interactive maps
column39: all of which can easily be printed or embedded (live) in a website - Heurist provides the html code required to embed results in a web page or CMS.Databases can easily be migrated later to a personal or institutional server. Since the data are stored in a standard MySQL database with a fixed and well-documented structure
column40: the data can be accessed directly via SQL from most programming languages independently of Heurist.Version 4.2 (Jan 2016 onwards) is available as a service via the Heurist website. Version 4 delivers a user-customisable interface of widgets
column41: along with better mapping and visualisation. Existing version 3 databases are bidirectionally compatible with version 4." NA

column1: 3572 "u3Ync0" "HT-Bookworm" "capturing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/capturing" "Q123819225" "capturing" "840" "HT-Bookworm" "Bookworm is a tool that visualizes language usage trends in repositories of digitized texts in a simple and powerful way. It is a tool for culturomic exploration through the observation of chronological trends for words and phrases in large digitized collections of textual documents with metadata facets.The world's great research libraries have
column2: over time
column3: carefully assembled a rich body of metadata pertaining to the books in their collections. Since the HTRC has access to volume-level metadata as well as volume-level content
column4: we have constructed a Bookworm of the HathiTrust Non-Google-digitized public domain (NGPD) corpus. We felt that setting up Bookworm with a HathiTrust corpus would provides scholarly researchers with the means of exploring trends.This tool enables scholars to discover new textual use patterns across the entire corpus. In the future
column5: we plan to ingest the entire HathiTrust corpus and continue to identify appropriate metadata to use for the faceted browsing. This tool will be particularly useful to scholars interested in books that are still under copyright - which is the case for most books published after 1923. Although these books will not be available for reading or downloading online
column6: working with individual words and phrases and tracking their occurrences through time will be useful to academic researchers
column8: sociologists and literary scholars.John Unsworth has noted that a fundamental goal of the humanities is appreciation: \"by paying attention to an object of interest
column11: notice things about it that have never been noticed before
column12: and increase its value\" (2004). Shifting from traditional close reading to a large-scale view of text presents a profound discomfort for humanities scholars
column13: due to the difficulty in retaining the same sensitivity to what is actually contained in the works being studied. HTRC-Bookworm will function as a link between quantitative analysis (distant reading) and close reading. According to Frederick Gibbs and Daniel Cohen
column14: \"any robust digital research methodology must allow the scholar to move easily between distant and close reading
column15: between the bird's eye view and the ground level of the texts themselves\" (2011). This is what HTRC-Bookworm intends to accomplish (within the limitations of applicable copyright laws.)Current limitations and future improvements:The current instantiation (the alpha version) of the HTRC-Bookworm is set up to work with only 250
column16: 000 out-of-copyright volumes from the HathiTrust NGPD corpus. Overall the HathiTrust has more than 11
column19: consisting of 420 billion pages.As a demonstration we have selected some metadata for use with this smaller corpus
column20: but we are open to feedback on improvements to this metadata.Our plan is to ingest the larger HathiTrust corpus and to allow facets to be selected based on HTRC worksets." NA

column1: What is it?

column1: Who is it for?

column1: 3681 "bksRC7" "INL BlackLab" "analyzing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/analyzing" "Q217602" "analyzing" "328" "INL BlackLab" "From the official BlackLab site: \"BlackLab is a corpus retrieval engine built on top of Apache Lucene. It allows fast
column2: complex searches with accurate hit highlighting on large
column3: tagged and annotated
column4: bodies of text. It was developed at the Institute of Dutch Lexicology (INL) to provide a fast and feature-rich search interface on our historical and contemporary text corpora. BlackLab is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.\" BlackLab is not an end-user application
column5: but an extension to Apache Lucene.  It requires programming experience to use.  Several sites have so far been built using BlackLab.  The BlackLab FAQ at https://github.com/INL/BlackLab/wiki/Frequently-Asked-Questions lists several of these. BlackLab is very useful as search engine for morphologically adorned corpora.  The principal search language syntax is similar to that of traditional corpus search engine tools such as the Corpus Workbench or the Sketch Engine.    " NA

column3: word choice and writing style analysis. It then reports on which writer the text most resembles. The tool requires at least two paragraphs of text for best results. At this time

column1: 3835 "tUkAbQ" "Juxta Commons" "collating" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/collating" "Q65770408" "collation" "880" "Juxta Commons" "The Juxta family of software (Juxta
column2: Juxta WS
column3: and Juxta Commons) allows you to compare and collate versions of the same textual work. Juxta Commons is an online space powered by the open-source Juxta Web Service that lets you collate sets of two or more texts and share online visualizations of the differences between them. Side-by-side or \"heat map\" visualizations can be viewed on the Juxta Commons site
column4: while embedding codes are available for sharing a compact version of the heat map visualization on your own blog or website. Collation results can also be output as an XML file with TEI parallel segmentation markup
column5: or as a Word document or HTML file with a base text and traditional textual apparatus. Development of Juxta Commons was sponsored by NINES." NA

column2: including photos and gifs. It provides a means
column3: by a draggable pane
column4: to see the changes and visually analyse the differences between the two images.It’s an adaptable storytelling tool that is ideal for highlighting then/now stories that explain slow changes over time (growth of a city skyline
column5: regrowth of a forest
column6: etc.) or before/after stories that show the impact of single dramatic events (natural disasters
column8: wars

column2: the web
column3: smartphones
column4: tablets
column5: augmented reality gear
column6: and virtual reality glasses. Kubity is powered by several proprietary 3D processing engines including \"Paragone\" and \"Etna\" that prepare the 3D file for transfer over mobile devices. 3D images can be uploaded and enhanced and used in an artificial reality environment. It also has augmented reality features. It can be used in architecture

column1: 4033 "Y5tEq2" "Lyra" "dataVisualization" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/dataVisualization" "Q6504956" "dataVisualization" "1510" "Lyra" "Lyra is an interactive environment that enables custom visualization design without writing any code. Graphical “marks” can be bound to data fields using property drop zones; dynamically positioned using connectors; and directly moved
column2: rotated
column3: and resized using handles. Lyra also provides a data pipeline interface for iterative visual specification of data transformations and layout algorithms. Lyra is more expressive than interactive systems like Tableau
column4: allowing designers to create custom visualizations comparable to hand-coded visualizations built with D3 or Processing. These visualizations can then be easily published and reused on the Web." NA

column1: 4051 "G2lYAK" "Manifold" "publishing" "https://vocabs.dariah.eu/tadirah/publishing" "Q3972943" "publishing" "1578" "Manifold" "Manifold Scholarship is an open-source publishing platform that enables authors and publishers a means to showcase and enhance the electronic content they already produce in their existing workflows: texts are displayed in a responsive
column2: elegant reader crafted for all modern browsers and devices—desktop and mobile. Powerful built-in annotation and commenting systems allow readers to annotate
column3: highlight
column4: discuss
column5: cite
column6: and share passages from any Manifold text. Resources that are foundational to a particular discussion but that are often tabled because of physical
column8: logistic
column9: or legal limitations can be layered dynamically and directly onto the digital text. And with Manifold
column10: a new kind of publication is possible
column11: one where authors create projects that grow iteratively and that are published online as they are created and then later in print
column12: when they have been codified as versions of record. In short
column13: Manifold transforms scholarly publications into living digital works." NA
